((SELECT ID FROM APPLICANT_DETAILS WHERE FILE_NUMBER = '6519'), 'From: Cassim Jadwat  Sent: Friday, 02 December 2022 09:42  To: Ariff Shaikh <Ariff.Shaikh@sanzaf.org.za>  Subject: RE: SANZAF National Office - DBN Complaint  AsSalaamUalaikum Ariff  _  As per the caseworker Sr. Rashida Patel & Humza Mthembu(Development):  	Mohamed Mtshali approached SANZAF on 29 April 2022.   	He was referred by Dr. Afzal Osman.  	He stated that he is a Rigging Engineer who was working in Qatar. His contract ended and he had returned home.  	He has two wives that live separately.  	His first wife(2 children) is gainfully employed at African Bank and pays her own bills.  	The second wife(1 Child) is unemployed.  	His initial request was R4500 for electricity. It was approved and paid by SANZAF.(29/04/2022)  	He was also assisted with a grocery hamper & R500 worth of vouchers.  	He stated that he had applied for several jobs in Qatar and was awaiting feedback.  	His second request was R10 000 for rent and R1 038.24 for electricity for May 2022.   	Dr. Osman paid R10 000 via SANZAF once off(he wishes to remain anonymous). SANZAF paid R1038.24 for electricity  16/05/2022.   	He was advised to bring his wife in for development/employment.  	He chose to join the business class. His request was for R57 000 to sell perfumes._  	The business committee only approved him for R5000 as he did not have any business premises or set customers.  	He made a profit of R1000 from the business._  	He then made a request for R40 000 for the business. He was requested to send a business report for two months of operation but he had spent the money on personal expenses.   	His business request was declined.  	He was advised to follow up with job opportunities. As per the development department his wife chose business over employment but dropped out of the business class. Br. Mohamed did not report back to development on any job applications._  	In the interim he moved from a cheaper flat to a more expensive flat as the landlord had sold the flat. This was done without consultation with SANZAF.  	Please note that during his business training, he was assisted with: _  1.	Rent  June(R4000), July(R4000), August(R4000), September(R4000), October(R2000).  2.	Groceries  April, May, June, July, August, November.  3.	Vouchers -  April(R500), May(R500), June(R500), August(R400), Solidarity voucher(R1000).  	The Shurra committee did not approve any further rental requests as they stated that he had not followed up on employment and had failed in his business. He is able bodied and needed to seek employment urgently as SANZAF gave him sufficient time and opportunities to empower himself.  	He stated that he doesnt want to work in South Africa as per his caseworker and the development department.  	When the caseworker contacted him to advise him that his last rental request was not approved, she encouraged him to return to SANZAFs development department with respect to employment.   	As per the caseworker, Mohamed stated Thank you so much for all the assistance he received from SANZAF. (22/11/2022).  	That was the last that SANZAF heard from Mohamed.  I hope that this report provides clarity with respect to the recipient, Mohamed Mtshali.  Shukran  Cassim', '2022-12-02', 'HAMZA', 'HAMZA', now(), now(), NULL),
